 <office:body>
  <office:text text:use-soft-page-breaks="true">
   <office:forms form:automatic-focus="false" form:apply-design-mode="false"/>
   <text:sequence-decls>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Illustration"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Table"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Text"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Drawing"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Figure"/>
   </text:sequence-decls>
   <text:p text:style-name="P2"><text:span text:style-name="T1">The War Diaries of </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T2">George Mesnard Parsons</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P3">16th Feb<text:span text:style-name="T3">r</text:span>uary 1915 to 4<text:span text:style-name="T4">th</text:span> October 1915</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P4" loext:marker-style-name="T5"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P4" loext:marker-style-name="T5">Please Note:</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5" loext:marker-style-name="T6"><text:span text:style-name="T7"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T8">{} </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T6">indicates clarification</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5" loext:marker-style-name="T6"><text:span text:style-name="T7"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T5">(</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T8">?</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T6">) Word added but with some doubt as difficult to read</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5" loext:marker-style-name="T6"><text:span text:style-name="T7"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T8">xxxx(?) </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T6">word of approximately” letters but unclear</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5" loext:marker-style-name="T6"><text:span text:style-name="T7"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T8">Axxxcxx(?) </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T6">word probable letters and approx. number of letter but unclear</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P6"><text:span text:style-name="T7"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T9">1/pxx </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T6">indicates diary number/page</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P7"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P9">Training School at Wisques, near St Omer</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"><text:tab/>A list of promotions in the camp came out today in which P.C.<text:span text:style-name="T10">H</text:span>ills Brocklehurst and Phillips were made corporals and Dan Willis a Lance <text:span text:style-name="T11">C</text:span>orpl. Hills and Philips have been L <text:span text:style-name="T12">Corpls</text:span> for a long time and everyone had given up the idea of them getting another chance. Perhaps the fact that <text:span text:style-name="T10">Innes</text:span> is a friend of the Hills family had something thing to do with it. I was disappointed that I came in for nothing and Brocklehurst got another stripe after my w<text:span text:style-name="T10">ork</text:span> in the new billet. However it it is a very difficult job selecting men for promotion. We have now had a weeks wretched weather. On Wednesday we had <text:span text:style-name="T10">a march</text:span> with packs the first time since <text:span text:style-name="T10">we</text:span> came back from the trenches. When I had got m<text:span text:style-name="T11">ine</text:span> adjusted properly I did not <text:span text:style-name="T10">feel </text:span>it rained all the time <text:span text:style-name="T11">&amp;</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P10"><text:span text:style-name="T13">I/p</text:span>2</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P11"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"><text:span text:style-name="T14">t</text:span>here was a biting wind.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P12">Friday 19 <text:span text:style-name="T15">Feb 1915</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P13"><text:span text:style-name="T16"><text:tab/>W</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">e hear very strong rumours that </text:span><text:bookmark text:name="firstHeading4"/><text:span text:style-name="T18">Messine</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">s </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">has been captured </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T20">but </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">have no confirmationof it. It is a fact though that the troops a re very active. </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T16">T</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">he </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T16">OURs</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> who are here tell us that all the other battalions </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">in </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">their division are being used, and the</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T20">y</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> are being kept in reserve here to go up to any part of the line whe</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T20">n</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> called upon. Sir John French has just published another d</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T22">e</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">spatch in which he makes a particular reference to the </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T16">A</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">rtists </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T16">R</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">ifles and their work as an OTC. This makes it even less probable than it was before that we will ever be used as a unit which means that we have </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T23">the</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> alternative of f</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T23">ooling</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> about here </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T23">for the</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> rest of the war </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T20">and </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">returning home with an ignominious record, or of taking a </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T22">C</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">ommission.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P14"><text:tab/>This no doubt is the heroic c<text:span text:style-name="T24">o</text:span>urse, but it means giving up everything. My ambition in life had been <text:span text:style-name="T24">firstly</text:span> to get a job with a sufficient salary to allow me to marry comfortably and beyond that to <text:span text:style-name="T24">be</text:span> able to educate my children as well I have been myself. But the</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P15">Notes</text:p>
   <text:h text:style-name="P16" text:outline-level="1"><text:bookmark text:name="firstHeading"/>OTC Officers&apos; Training Corps</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P17"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P10"><text:span text:style-name="T13">I/p</text:span><text:page-number text:select-page="current">3</text:page-number></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P14"><text:span text:style-name="T25">C</text:span>ommission business destroys all that. Serving out here in the ranks entail<text:span text:style-name="T26">ed</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T27">a</text:span> risk but considering the circumstances a risk that anyone would naturally take. Taking a <text:span text:style-name="T25">C</text:span>ommission <text:span text:style-name="T10">however</text:span> raises the risk of being hit from about one in <text:span text:style-name="T25">1 in </text:span>5<text:span text:style-name="T25">0</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T27">to 3 </text:span><text:s/><text:span text:style-name="T27">in 5, </text:span>and all as<text:span text:style-name="T10">pirations</text:span> for the future would <text:span text:style-name="T27">perforce</text:span> have to be given up. Beyond that the amount of use <text:span text:style-name="T10">one </text:span>would be does not seem to me to warrant the risk<text:span text:style-name="T27">; the </text:span>chances are at least even that you <text:span text:style-name="T27">are</text:span> out of action <text:span text:style-name="T27">before </text:span>you <text:span text:style-name="T12">are </text:span>any real use. Then again I do not honestly consider that I am in any way cut out f<text:span text:style-name="T25">or</text:span> an army officer. Whatever ability I have been <text:span text:style-name="T10">endowed</text:span> with is <text:span text:style-name="T12">of </text:span>the slow order. <text:span text:style-name="T10">W</text:span>hen it c<text:span text:style-name="T12">o</text:span>me<text:span text:style-name="T12">s</text:span> to a decision being required <text:span text:style-name="T10">the</text:span> crisis would be over <text:span text:style-name="T10">before</text:span> my slow brain <text:span text:style-name="T12">has </text:span>started to work. I am <text:span text:style-name="T12">a </text:span>hopeless failure when taken unawares.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P18">Tuesday the 23<text:span text:style-name="T4">rd</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T27">February</text:span> <text:tab/>On the ammunition guard again. Surprised in the morning by Edward Horsley looking us up the<text:span text:style-name="T10">se</text:span> </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P19"><text:span text:style-name="T17">No4 draft arrived <text:tab/>He left with the first batch in November with </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T23">C</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">risp etc, <text:tab/>and is in the </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T28">2nd</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> Gordon</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T28">s</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> now down at </text:span><text:bookmark text:name="firstHeading1"/><text:span text:style-name="T29">La Bassée</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">; they have very bad <text:tab/>trenches but have not had at</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_La_Bassée" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_La_Bass%C3%A9e</text:a></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P20">I/p4</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P21"><text:span text:style-name="T30">at </text:span>all an exciting time on the whole. He told <text:span text:style-name="T10">u</text:span>s many interesting things. Cris<text:span text:style-name="T31">p</text:span> was killed in the trenches next to his battalion. <text:span text:style-name="T10">I</text:span>t was about Christmas time while there was a truce opposite them, but further along the <text:span text:style-name="T10">line</text:span> there was no truce. C<text:span text:style-name="T32">risp</text:span> with others was on the parapet and was shot from German trenches 500 yards away. Rendered unconscious at once and died an hour after.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"><text:tab/>The<text:span text:style-name="T31">ir</text:span> trenches a<text:span text:style-name="T10">re</text:span> so bad where they are that they ha<text:span text:style-name="T10">ve</text:span> been abandoned except for small watching groups. The rest of the battalion are in re<text:span text:style-name="T31">d</text:span>ou<text:span text:style-name="T31">bt</text:span>s behind. He did not throw much light on the commission controversy but said that <text:span text:style-name="T10">none</text:span> of them would be promoted it was not worth it se<text:span text:style-name="T30">niority</text:span> was all awry. Senior officers were under the command of juniors. His brother <text:tab/>Oscar had been wounded in the left shoulder in a very bad trench <text:span text:style-name="T33">but w</text:span>as about ready for duty again now. He w<text:span text:style-name="T33">ould</text:span> report to the third Battalion and might be sent anywhere, even to <text:span text:style-name="T33">K</text:span>itcheners army.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"><text:tab/>I <text:span text:style-name="T34">again</text:span> spen<text:span text:style-name="T34">t</text:span> a lot of time in the brewery</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P20">I/p<text:page-number text:select-page="current">5</text:page-number></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P22"><text:span text:style-name="T35">a</text:span>nd learnt a little more about their <text:span text:style-name="T33">system </text:span>which I have said something about <text:span text:style-name="T33">under 1</text:span>0 Jan.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P23"><text:tab/>I found out the exact quantity they use 14 sac<text:span text:style-name="T33">ks</text:span> of malt 60 <text:span text:style-name="T33">Kilos</text:span> ea<text:span text:style-name="T35">ch,</text:span> Hops 20 k<text:span text:style-name="T33">ilos</text:span> this makes 370 h<text:span text:style-name="T33">ectos</text:span> of beer. Unfortunately I don&apos;t know if they use any sugar but I did not se<text:span text:style-name="T36">e</text:span> any. If not this seems to correspond to a ho<text:span text:style-name="T33">p</text:span> rate of eight pounds per quarter. They put five sa<text:span text:style-name="T33">cks</text:span> of ground m<text:span text:style-name="T36">a</text:span>lt into a cold t<text:span text:style-name="T36">an</text:span> then start one quartz underneath at 70° C (160F) on. Two more sacks are then put in <text:span text:style-name="T33">and </text:span>the rakes are then started. <text:span text:style-name="T36">H</text:span>e stop<text:span text:style-name="T33">ped</text:span> the qu<text:span text:style-name="T36">liq</text:span> when he had a mash <text:span text:style-name="T33">of</text:span> about <text:span text:style-name="T33">1</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T37">¾</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T35">Ltrs per</text:span> quarter. He kept th<text:span text:style-name="T33">e</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T33">r</text:span>ak<text:span text:style-name="T36">e</text:span>s still going. The first in<text:span text:style-name="T33">itial</text:span> was 60°C (140°F) . After a stand of 1 <text:span text:style-name="T38">½</text:span> hours ra<text:span text:style-name="T33">k</text:span>es going all the time <text:span text:style-name="T33">he</text:span> started the boiling water slowly and temp <text:span text:style-name="T33">was 65</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">º</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T33">C (140</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">º</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T33">F), then speeded up the rakes to stir up the mash at the bottom until the heat <text:s/>reached 70</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">º(160F). He st</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40">ood</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39"> for one hour and drew the goods right down before </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40">Sp</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T38">arging</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39"> .For sparge be used boiling liq. </text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P24"><text:span text:style-name="T38">27/</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T41">2/15</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T42"><text:tab/><text:tab/>I had </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">a great surprise this morning wh</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T42">en</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39"> I </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T42">got back from </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T38">Saturday </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T42">platoon drill </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39"><text:s/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T42">I was </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39">t</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T42">old</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39"> tha</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T42">t</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39"> Jack Chi</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T42">ck</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T42">&amp;</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T39"> Maurice had been over <text:tab/> <text:s text:c="4"/>for me.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P25">I/p<text:page-number text:select-page="current">6</text:page-number></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P26"><text:span text:style-name="T43">Maurice</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T44">c</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">a</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T44">me</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> after me again. It appears </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">that Jack who is attached to the </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">G</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">uards Brigade </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T46">II</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T46">D</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">iv, had to come over here on business. He had </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">a </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">car at his disposal and picked up M</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T46">aurice</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> at Levant</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T47">i</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">e. They stood me a good lunch at the hotel </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T46">Faucon</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> and then took </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">me </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">down to the </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T48">Méteren</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">while Jack was engaged with the </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">Mayor</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">. I went for a walk with </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T43">Maurice</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> down the Mont </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">des Cats road</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">. He had been in the firing line trenches on the </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T47">Marne</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> but was now at </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">Levantie</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> working on roads an</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">d</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">exposed</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> to occasional shellfire. We rejoin</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">ed</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> Jack and visited a farm that had been accidentally burnt down by our troops billeted in it, and then they b</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T47">r</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">ought me back to </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T48">Bailleul</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">.</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> Jack present</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">ing</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> me with </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">2</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> bottles of </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">B</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">lack </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">&amp;</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">W</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">hite.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P27">28/<text:span text:style-name="T13">2/15</text:span> Sund<text:span text:style-name="T15">a</text:span>y <text:span text:style-name="T49">B</text:span>eautiful clear day with high wind. Walked out to Mont Rou<text:span text:style-name="T50">ge</text:span> </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P27"><text:s text:c="15"/>s<text:span text:style-name="T50">plendid</text:span> view. Could see <text:span text:style-name="T50">Y</text:span>pres <text:span text:style-name="T51">quite clearly and see the damage </text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P27"><text:span text:style-name="T51"><text:tab/> <text:s text:c="5"/>done to its towers also th</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T52">e</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T51"> battered villages of Dichebush and </text:span><text:bookmark text:name="firstHeading2"/><text:span text:style-name="T51"><text:tab/><text:tab/> <text:s text:c="5"/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T53">W</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T54">y</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T53">tschaete. </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T51">Just in </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T55">front</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T51"> of the latter we could make out the <text:tab/><text:tab/> <text:s text:c="5"/>Germa</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T56">n </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T51">trenches </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T55">&amp;</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T51"> while we were up there a 4.7 between us and <text:s text:c="4"/><text:tab/> <text:s text:c="5"/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T55">Ke</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T51">mmel opened fire on </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T52">them</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T51">. </text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P28"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.sheffieldsoldierww1.co.uk/YourSoldier/Charlesworth_T.html" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T17">http://www.sheffieldsoldierww1.co.uk/YourSoldier/Charlesworth_T.html</text:span></text:a></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P28"><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capture_of_Wytschaete" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T17">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capture_of_Wytschaete</text:span></text:a></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kemmelberg</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P8"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P29"><text:span text:style-name="T13">I/p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T57">7</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30">It blew it to pieces with the chauffeur</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30"><text:tab/>The class up for the lewis at present includes parties <text:s/></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30">from the 18th 22 26 and 37 Divs. To-night we have been told that the 22nd Div men are to leave tomorrow this is most unusual and we can only surmise that they must be off to Servia.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30"><text:tab/>It appears from the reception committees look, which I had a good look at when I was on that job last Saturday that the British force out here is at present organise as a Army courts each of three Dives of influence artillery etc. The numbers being1,2,3,4,5,6,7 10 &amp; 12 the divisions are 1 - 28 except 10 11 &amp; 13 to 16 also 37 and the territorial gears 4647, 48, 49, 50, 51 in addition there is the guards Div Canadian DW and two Indian Divs Then there is the cavalry corps or 3 Div and the Indian Cav of 2 Divs</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30">Saturday<text:tab/> we now hear that the 2<text:span text:style-name="T57">8</text:span> Div are also being sent to Serbia.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30">Monday<text:tab/>our last squads left on Saturday so that we have now been free but two days. Today I have had a very busy day collecting mess huts are pretty bad job under any circumstances but the</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P31">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T58">8</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">and Marth<text:span text:style-name="T59">e</text:span> wa<text:span text:style-name="T59">ited</text:span> on us. We had some of M<text:span text:style-name="T59">adames</text:span> excellent wine and finished with Johnny Walker soda which M<text:span text:style-name="T60">adame,</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T59">g</text:span>ot for us. P<text:span text:style-name="T59">ulverman</text:span> came down and play<text:span text:style-name="T59">ed</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T59">t</text:span>o us after dinner, he is a wonderful<text:span text:style-name="T60">ly</text:span> clever pianist.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">Monday, 1 March <text:span text:style-name="T61">W</text:span>e went for a route march to <text:span text:style-name="T61">Vieux Berquin. <text:s/>I</text:span>t was a fine morning with a strong wind. <text:span text:style-name="T61">W</text:span>e had lunch out there <text:line-break/>? <text:span text:style-name="T61">&amp;</text:span> came back through <text:span text:style-name="T62">Notre B</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T63">oon</text:span>. <text:span text:style-name="T61">A</text:span> new l<text:span text:style-name="T61">i</text:span>st of emb<text:span text:style-name="T61">a</text:span>r<text:span text:style-name="T61">os </text:span>was waiting for us when we got back <text:span text:style-name="T61">including </text:span>Brocklehurst and Strod<text:span text:style-name="T61">e</text:span> who have been so loud in their condemnation of the <text:span text:style-name="T61">O</text:span>TC. <text:span text:style-name="T61">n</text:span>ow a<text:span text:style-name="T61">las</text:span> they have given way, also <text:span text:style-name="T61">B</text:span>rown. Now <text:span text:style-name="T61">a</text:span>part from specialists the on<text:span text:style-name="T61">ly</text:span> men<text:span text:style-name="T61">bers </text:span>of <text:span text:style-name="T61">No1</text:span> section who remain are Sgt. Wil<text:span text:style-name="T64">liams,</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T61">Gadsby</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T61">&amp; </text:span>myself <text:span text:style-name="T59">and</text:span> M.<text:span text:style-name="T61">A</text:span> Hills Ballard <text:span text:style-name="T61">&amp;</text:span> Bri<text:span text:style-name="T61">ndley</text:span> are office<text:span text:style-name="T59">r</text:span>s servants. In the whole company bar special<text:span text:style-name="T59">i</text:span>s<text:span text:style-name="T59">ts</text:span> we have now 10 NCOs <text:span text:style-name="T61">&amp;</text:span> eight privates who came over here with the battalion. <text:span text:style-name="T61">T</text:span>hat is in the old F company. <text:span text:style-name="T61">a</text:span>nd PC <text:span text:style-name="T61">H</text:span>ills <text:span text:style-name="T61">who </text:span>has left to go to <text:s/>9 <text:span text:style-name="T61">Platoon</text:span>. The numbers who have taken commission<text:span text:style-name="T61">s</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T59">or </text:span>are now in training is 37. <text:span text:style-name="T61">4 </text:span>being in England. In addition to this</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P31">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T58">9</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32">there are lot from the drafts, and two men left us to go to <text:span text:style-name="T31">St Omer</text:span> as machine gun <text:span text:style-name="T31">in</text:span>structurs. I <text:span text:style-name="T65">may</text:span> here rema<text:span text:style-name="T65">rk</text:span> that of the five who took commissions out here in Nov, 2 were killed and one wounded in <text:span text:style-name="T31">2</text:span> months. <text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T31">W</text:span>e walked out to <text:span text:style-name="T31">Mont Rouge</text:span> in the afternoon but it was not so clear as on Sunday <text:span text:style-name="T66">and </text:span>we could only just see Y<text:span text:style-name="T31">pres</text:span>. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32"><text:tab/>We saw the <text:span text:style-name="T31">6”</text:span> guns firing again <text:span text:style-name="T31">T</text:span>hey <text:span text:style-name="T65">are</text:span> rapidly putting up a lo<text:span text:style-name="T31">t</text:span>s of h<text:span text:style-name="T31">u</text:span>ts <text:span text:style-name="T65">at</text:span> of Lo<text:span text:style-name="T31">ure</text:span> to hold about 20 men each and are widening the metal surface of the road as <text:span text:style-name="T66">if</text:span>, in<text:span text:style-name="T66">preperation</text:span> for <text:s/>great event<text:span text:style-name="T66">s</text:span>. We saw parts of a new 6” H<text:span text:style-name="T67">o</text:span>u<text:span text:style-name="T65">wiz</text:span>er in Lo<text:span text:style-name="T65">i</text:span>re just arrived <text:span text:style-name="T67">by</text:span> traction engine <text:span text:style-name="T65">it </text:span>is going to be placed somewhere near there. <text:span text:style-name="T67">W</text:span>alked into <text:span text:style-name="T67">A</text:span>rm<text:span text:style-name="T67">enteres</text:span> with <text:span text:style-name="T67">Gadsby</text:span> D<text:span text:style-name="T67">ou</text:span>son, <text:span text:style-name="T67">Figg &amp;</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T67">F</text:span>elgate. <text:span text:style-name="T67">L</text:span>a<text:span text:style-name="T67">rgish </text:span>town with good shops <text:span text:style-name="T67">&amp; </text:span>several large breweries. showed signs of bombardment <text:span text:style-name="T67">all</text:span> one side of the <text:span text:style-name="T67">m</text:span>ain Street being more or less <text:span text:style-name="T67">k</text:span>no<text:span text:style-name="T67">cked</text:span> about but <text:span text:style-name="T67">very</text:span> little damage had been done <text:span text:style-name="T67">to</text:span> big buildings; m<text:span text:style-name="T67">u</text:span>st <text:span text:style-name="T67">be a</text:span> prominent town in peacetime. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32"><text:span text:style-name="T67"><text:tab/>T</text:span>erritorial<text:span text:style-name="T67">s</text:span> mu<text:span text:style-name="T67">ch in</text:span> evidence LR<text:span text:style-name="T67">B</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T67">are</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T67">these </text:span>and while we <text:span text:style-name="T65">were</text:span> there</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P31">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T58">10</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P33"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P34"><text:span text:style-name="T68">Leicsters</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T69">&amp;</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T68">N</text:span>ot<text:span text:style-name="T68">ts</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T14">&amp; Derby </text:span>arrive<text:span text:style-name="T68">d</text:span>. Got</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P34"><text:s/><text:span text:style-name="T68">a</text:span> lift back <text:span text:style-name="T68">by</text:span> motor Lor<text:span text:style-name="T68">ry</text:span> and bus which had taken <text:span text:style-name="T68">Leisterers</text:span> up. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P34"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P35"><text:span text:style-name="T13">6/3/15 </text:span>Saturday<text:span text:style-name="T70"><text:tab/></text:span>We had a lecture from t<text:span text:style-name="T69">yre</text:span> on the history of modern tactics. He told us that we were to commence <text:span text:style-name="T68">a </text:span>systematic course of training elementary at first but <text:span text:style-name="T69">pro-</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P34"><text:span text:style-name="T69">pressive</text:span>. This together with <text:span text:style-name="T69">e</text:span>nquiries as to who has been to the trenches and who has not, have <text:span text:style-name="T68">given</text:span> much encouragement to our hopes that we will be used as a unit.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P36">Sunday <text:span text:style-name="T68">7th</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T68">March</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P33"><text:span text:style-name="T71">Walk to </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T72">D</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T71">o</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T73">ulieu</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T71"> with </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T72">H</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T71">ills </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T74">A</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T71"> <text:s/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T72">furious</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T71"> bombardment was proceeding.</text:span> We were told by others who had walked out in the other direction that all our guns were going <text:s/>h<text:span text:style-name="T68">ard</text:span> and also that the 15” gun <text:span text:style-name="T68">at Loire</text:span> had been doing good work although the Germans had found out where it was <text:span text:style-name="T68">and had got so</text:span> near to it that it was decided to shift it; how<text:span text:style-name="T75">ever</text:span> true this <text:span text:style-name="T75">is it </text:span>is impossible to say; everything points to great events <text:span text:style-name="T68">im</text:span>pending <text:span text:style-name="T68">4</text:span> French gun biplanes have appeared here and</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P37"><text:span text:style-name="T76">(</text:span>Note 15” fired 40 rounds<text:span text:style-name="T76">)</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P31">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T58">11</text:span></text:p>
