   <text:p text:style-name="P71">I/p35</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68">on guard on <text:span text:style-name="T15">No</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T15">6</text:span> examining post with <text:span text:style-name="T15">Hamaford</text:span> Simpson Robinson. <text:span text:style-name="T15">I</text:span>t was a cold dy and we were very glad to sit inside by the fire</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"><text:tab/>When we came off the next day I had another afternoon in the ri<text:span text:style-name="T15">ver</text:span> with PC and MA hills it was <text:span text:style-name="T15">a</text:span> windy day. We made a thorough ex<text:span text:style-name="T15">ploration</text:span> of the canals and lakes out towards <text:span text:style-name="T15">Nieurlet.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"><text:tab/>On Friday we got the sad use that Barry joined us with the last draft has died in hospital. He was sent there with German measles but M complications arrived</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"><text:tab/>He was a splendid fellow tall and big the only 19 years of age. I had him on guard runs and thought him an excellent fellow in every way. His death has upset us all very much.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"><text:tab/>One member of him makes room has just got served fresh job Wallace. He joined us with the number four draft in said and I was in my billet at their loan he is a rough sort of fellow but soon became one of the leading spirits in the room. He has been all over the world and has a in explorable stock of anecdotes the son of a French mother he was educated at St. O’Mara here at the</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68">https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo/wisques.html</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72">I/p3<text:span text:style-name="T112">6</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68">and speaks French like a native. Latterly he was just spent many years in Germany and speaks th<text:span text:style-name="T15">at</text:span> language also he was in Cologne when war was declared and had an adventurous time getting; <text:s/>away his <text:span text:style-name="T15">loss</text:span> the Frenchman was arrested and gave over to his charge niece of his in English girl Wallace got hold of a motor launch and with his girl and another Englishman managed to after several adventures which he details in such amus<text:span text:style-name="T15">ing</text:span> manner to get down the Rhine into Holland and then<text:span text:style-name="T15">ce</text:span> to England.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68">He was has been a permanent sanitary men since we have been in <text:span text:style-name="T113">St Omar</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T113">and </text:span>has become quite popular with the AS<text:span text:style-name="T113">C</text:span> men in the barracks here one <text:span text:style-name="T113">day </text:span>a man came up to him <text:span text:style-name="T113">&amp; comming out a</text:span> heap of rubbish told him that rubbish wasn’t not he put there <text:span text:style-name="T113">&amp;</text:span> he must move it. Wallace looked him up and down <text:span text:style-name="T113">&amp;</text:span> s<text:span text:style-name="T113">eeing</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T113">no </text:span>stripes in his sleeve told him that his men had just the rubbish then who the be did he think he was telling talking to if the wanted the be rubbish said he warned could at least get to move himself. The men nearly</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72">I/p3<text:span text:style-name="T112">7</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68">collapsed in w<text:span text:style-name="T113">rath</text:span> but retired. He was surrounded by an admiring crowd who shook him by the hand for telling off their sergeant major!! now he has got a proper plum job. He is assistant Clark to the Sir John French’s military see them <text:span text:style-name="T113">Lam</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T15">b</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T113">ton</text:span> is <text:span text:style-name="T113">to as</text:span> he helps the generals <text:span text:style-name="T113">c</text:span>l<text:span text:style-name="T113">e</text:span>rk a service official in <text:span text:style-name="T113">civil </text:span>life who details society gossip to him in the intervals of work.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P68"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P73"><text:span text:style-name="T108"><text:tab/>On s</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">aturday</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108"> I had </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">No4</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108"> pos</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">t</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108"> the most important one </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">It </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108">is at the junction of the roads to all </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">to </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T115">Boulogne</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114"> &amp; </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">Hazebrouck</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T116"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T117">so </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108">gets practical </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">all the </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108">traffic in the town. It was the </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">1st May so </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108">I had a lot of trouble with people with </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">passes</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108"> which </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">expired </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108">the day before. I made one mistake but as I was turning in a dispatch rider came along with no pas</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">s</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">at all after a </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108">se</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">arching </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108">inquiry I had </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">him </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108">through but </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">o</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108">mitted to take his name or any other particulars, this arrived me so much after</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">wards </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108"><text:s/>that I </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">did</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108"> not got to sleep. I had Townsend as a lance corporal he </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">k</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108">e</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">p</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108">t </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">up</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">till</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108"> 1:30 I did get the rest. <text:tab/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">On </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108">Sunday afternoon I </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">kept</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108"> a short walk with MA </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T118">H</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108">ills to lead to </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">Layes</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108">mash with count</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">y</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T108"> is very</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P67"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72">I/p3<text:span text:style-name="T112">8</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P74">pretty out there especially now with the trees just coming out. It is very much like England. It was a very pleasant relief to see <text:span text:style-name="T113">hedges</text:span> after the Country we have been in. I hear never appreciated <text:span text:style-name="T113">hedges</text:span> so much before.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P74"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P73"><text:span text:style-name="T119"><text:tab/>On Wednesday I was on guard at the treasury again. When we were re</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">leaved</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119"> on Thurs </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">are</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119"> found there had been a nice pa</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">rse in barracks </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119">the day before as more men had been </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">wanted </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119">to to go to </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">Hazebrouck </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">&amp;</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119"> none could be found. I found that Han</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">s</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119">ford </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">&amp;</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119"> Clayton had gone from my room this brings our numbers down to </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">6</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119">. We are getting a very short of men. There are 50 away at the machine gun school at <text:s/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T120">Wisques</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119"> on fatigue duty and another 50 are down with measles and there are now about 80 </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">at</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119"> <text:s/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T116">Hazebrouck </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119">GHQ ha</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">ve</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119"> moved the</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">re</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119"> temporary as there is some important move on foot and our people are doing </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">guard</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119"> e</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">tc</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119">. This leaves us with very few men indeed and we have two fall back on the </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">Colonels class</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">for</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119"> duties </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T114">even </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T119">then most of them men get a guard every three days we are expecting a</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P75"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P75"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P75">Battle of St. Julien (Ypres) ends (see April 24th). </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72">I/p3<text:span text:style-name="T112">9</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P74">new draft but they ease is as yet no news of it. When it does come the men will not have gone through them musket<text:span text:style-name="T113">y</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T113">and will </text:span>have to teach them.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P74"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P75"><text:tab/>The weather once we have been in <text:span text:style-name="T121">St Omer </text:span>has really been wonderful good we have a hardly had any rain till this week it has been gradually getting hotter and the appearance of the County hasn’t changed from winter to spring. On Friday Wednesday <text:span text:style-name="T113">&amp;</text:span> Thursday we had a thunderstorm but yesterday <text:span text:style-name="T113">&amp;</text:span> today have been perfect days</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P74"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P74"><text:tab/>We have heard very heavy firing all day today so suppose there’s been another big “wind up”</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P74"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P75"><text:tab/>I am very much relieved to find that Mr. Lloyd George latest scheme of a beer <text:span text:style-name="T113">surtax</text:span> has been abandoned through the pressure brought to bear against it <text:span text:style-name="T113">&amp; </text:span>the <text:span text:style-name="T113">N</text:span>ationalists.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P75"><text:tab/> <text:span text:style-name="T113">I</text:span>t has indeed at prepos<text:span text:style-name="T113">terous</text:span> scheme</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P74"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P75"><text:span text:style-name="T113"><text:tab/>T</text:span>he news lately has b<text:span text:style-name="T113">ad</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T113">The</text:span> Germans by using <text:span text:style-name="T113">asphlyxiating gasses</text:span> drove us back north of <text:span text:style-name="T113">ypres</text:span> about a fortnight ago and have been making repeated attacks since on Hill 60 <text:s/><text:span text:style-name="T113">miles</text:span> South of <text:s/><text:span text:style-name="T122">Hazebrouck.</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T113">N</text:span>ow we hear that they have captured it <text:span text:style-name="T113">and</text:span> we are struggling</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T112">40</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P74">to retake it on top of this comes <text:span text:style-name="T113">news </text:span>use of <text:span text:style-name="T113">the </text:span>s<text:span text:style-name="T113">inking</text:span> of the Lusitania. This news from the Eastern front is not at all good, the<text:span text:style-name="T113">r</text:span>e the Germans claim to have made a ra<text:span text:style-name="T113">id</text:span> nearly as far as <text:span text:style-name="T113">Riga.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P74"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P74"><text:tab/>As a result of this very bad openings of the spring campaign, shows as it do<text:span text:style-name="T113">es</text:span> that the <text:span text:style-name="T113">g</text:span>erman <text:span text:style-name="T113">power </text:span><text:s/>is far from broken, we are all rather despondent about the ultimate’s issue of the war and the time it takes to finish it</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P74"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P75"><text:tab/>O<text:span text:style-name="T113">n guard at No4 </text:span><text:s/><text:span text:style-name="T113">again vague rumours of British success come to us getting more precise </text:span>a<text:span text:style-name="T113">s the day goes on. Kitchener, Churchill &amp; Joffre aew said to be at</text:span> said to be at <text:span text:style-name="T122">Hazebrouck</text:span> with French.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P74"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P74"><text:tab/>No <text:span text:style-name="T113">news</text:span> get<text:span text:style-name="T113">s</text:span> through about what is going on in the firing line and <text:span text:style-name="T113">we get </text:span>no confirmation of the rumors we have heard <text:span text:style-name="T113">H</text:span>ills <text:span text:style-name="T123">for instance </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T113">was on guard at the </text:span>general staff, and was told by a capt of the signal office that the Germans had withdrawn all their reserves from the Western front <text:span text:style-name="T113">&amp;</text:span> taking them across to Russia. We had <text:span text:style-name="T113">sarged </text:span>the opportunity to take an attack <text:span text:style-name="T113">all along the</text:span> <text:span text:style-name="T113">line &amp; </text:span><text:s/>w<text:span text:style-name="T113">ere</text:span> doing very well as also w<text:span text:style-name="T113">ere</text:span> the French</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P74"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P76"><text:span text:style-name="T124">The French officials </text:span>communiqué <text:span text:style-name="T124"><text:s/>claims </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T125">an</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P74"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T112">41</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P77">advance over a front of 7 Kilometers to a depth of 4 Kilometers in places but nothing has been published of any British suc<text:span text:style-name="T123">c</text:span>ess and we of it</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P78">11 May Tuesday </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P78"><text:tab/>Fortsham Green &amp; Hannsford leave today for the school at Blendques. They were all in my billit at 130 in Bailleul and Green &amp; Hammeld have been with me ever since they have been in France. They are all very nice fellows. An extremely sorry to lose them. The room now is very empty . I only have <text:span text:style-name="T123">W</text:span>allis Ro<text:span text:style-name="T123">s</text:span>elli &amp; Williams. The first we see very little of he <text:span text:style-name="T123">I</text:span> here for breakfast and sometimes looking in the afternoon but does not yet in at night untill are all in bed. Rosceth is on others batman &amp; Waltham who has been of parade for months with a poi<text:span text:style-name="T123">s</text:span>oned hand has just become available for duties again. We are expecting another draft shortly</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P78"><text:tab/>Wallis in a burst of confidence tells us that a week ago when the Germans first started the use of gasses, Frence was seriously discussing a withdrawal of three miles at least along a </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P78"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T112">42</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P79"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P80">section of the front but <text:span text:style-name="T126">i</text:span>t was decided that the moral effect would be to bad he also says that in the recent fighting as there general was <text:span text:style-name="T126">cashvered for not bringing up his reserves in Time.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P81"><text:tab/>On Tuesday evening I had a stroll with Raseth down to the canal we saw a nest extrordinarily craft these a good stream barge with a large dechhouse. It was painted grey &amp; there was a RE felow abroad. I asked him if it had been specailly built for the army he said it had and asked us aboard &amp; showed us around. She was a wed telegraph boat splendidly fitted out engine boiler room night aft; Then came a bophins calm where the after hold should be. fitted up with some twenty beds very closely pached but very comfortable in front of two cabins for 4 NC O &amp; then a testing room for telegraphic apparatus. These quarters were for the telegraph staff. There was a hold about as large a a ordinary railing barge hold &amp; forcastle for the crew. House the staffs quarters the dechhouse there was a decent saloon for the use of the 1st Lieut in charge</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P81"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P72">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T112">43</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P82"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P81">two cabins one for him &amp; one for the serg major also a galley &amp; a well fitted office The fellow who took us round was an electrical engineer employed before the war on railway signalling in South America, He came home to join &amp; had just come out to join this boat on its arrival here. He was in Age of the electrical stress testing work. The boat was accompanied by another just the same size but having a lot two holds &amp; no accommodation for technical staff and their work was to be laying telegraphs along near the canal. It was really a wonderful example of the through way in which the Government was going about things such a thing had never been thought of before. I think I have said before that the army is using the canals a lot &amp; has bought over a lot of English tugs motor boats for the work &amp; they have also fitted out several barges for wounded &amp; they must certainly provide an ideal method for bringing the bad cases back. I am at present acting as platform sergeant </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P81"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P43">I/p44</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P83"><text:span text:style-name="T127">Serg William has gone down with measles. Hunter has gone to Havelock of course Captl Bracklehurst has left for the school. 13 Thurs. Oh very poor: found that a dispute had cropped up between madam at the Isammetel there and our guards. As I have said before she always said she was too busy to cook for us, &amp; we used to cook on a stove in the Isammetel. This however did not suit some of our gentlemen and it appears they went to a cottage nearby &amp; got their food cooked there. Then one night the guard took night at seeing beetles emerge from the fire place and scouted down the road to an Isammetel about a quarter of a mile further out. This proved to be too far away so yesterday the guard was ordered to return. Madam in conversation this morning betrayed away cheap dishes of the neighbouring cottage where the food was cooked &amp; said she was willing to cook for us if it did not interfere with her work in the kitchen. Had one incident of an amusing nature though it might have been serious. The supply wagon ran into the sentry box when the sentry was in it and knocked it right over the sentry managed to get </text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P84">I/p45</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P85">14/4/15 clear some how or other.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P85"><text:tab/>Very much suprised to hear in the evening that MH Hills name was in the first for the next officers class after he had told me he did not want to be in it only last Wednesday He is the last man in the platoon who came out with us who has not gone or got a special job</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P85">15/4/15 Had a walk in afternoon out to Helfaut &amp; Bilques to revisit the places where we were bilited last November The country out there is charming now. There were a lot of the New Army Artillery at Helfeut covering the place where we has a parade service. I had a drink in the Estamine we used to frequent the woman remembered us.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P85"><text:tab/>I came back through Blondeque the plavce where the cadet school is There were a lot of new army Gordons &amp; Cameronicans there It is a picturace place.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P85"><text:tab/>We has just turned n that mnight when I was awakaned &amp; told that the expected draft had arrived In true military style they had been taken through here in the morning onto Baillend They seem to be more about the night age than the last draft but they</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P84">I/p46</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P85">have done no shooting. I had to find room for 6 in our platoon rooms – this was easy enough</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P85">16/4/15 Had a walk with M A Hills out to Wisques where the machine gun school is; It is very pretty out there. We got up into a rise could look right across to Helfaut. The artillery had gone</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P85">17/4/15 On No4 Examining Post Once again there are great rumour of British success. Wallis told me this morning that they had received a wire from Kitchener which showed that Frence had expected to make a advance &amp; Kitchener wanted to know “what about it” He seemed to think it was worked upon as a case of now or never The Germans he said had made their trenches 15ft deep.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P85"><text:tab/>During the moring we wre told there was consternation that the battachs because men were wanted to go up to the front. Bring back German prisoners. Every available man was requested but I was washed out. A lot of wounded convoys have gone through but of them things gave been very</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P84">I/p47</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">quiet indeed. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:soft-page-break/><text:tab/>We get all sorts of rumours emanating from good sources that Katherine is not satisfied with the way things are being conducted out here. They say he has sent Smith Donen &amp; Douglas Doug home &quot;for a rest&quot; &amp; has told French that he wants a rest too. Wed 19 Dec 25 </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:tab/>Had a heart to head talk with Oottle. He want for me to tell me that L. Sgt Martin was being promoted to Lance Sergeant. Martin was made a Lance Sgt at the Tower &amp; came out with us but he just after Xmas he went home ill. While he was away I got my second stripe. Oottle wanted to tell me that no slight was intended to me by promoting him the reason being that but for his bad luck he would have been made a Sgt before me. He told me also that when Grouse was made Sergeant in place of Cook who has joined the officers club I would consider myself senior Corporal, taking pre- cedence over both Hiller &amp; Phillips. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:tab/>I took the opportunity of asking him to put my name down as a candidate for a machine gun instructorship at Wisques. He said he would. We spoke of Godsh &amp; I assured him that he would </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P86">I/p48</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">be an excellent man for the same job being a mechanic &amp; trade and as man who would win respect among any class. 20. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T128">Grouse</text:span> has had to go off to hospital with his eyes so I have to take over Orderly Sergeant from him. I have to stay in all day so as to be at hand if any sudden emergency arises &amp; we have to supply men I have to attend all parades, see that all men are present punctually and report all present to the S.M. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:tab/>At 4:45 I go to the Orderly Room to discuss tomorrow duties with the S.M. We go in take our hats off and sit down. He tells us the NCOs detailed for guards and how many men we must supply. They we go away to arrange which men shall go for each We go visit the SM again at 6:30. He then reads out the Battalion orders we taking them down to his dictation. That done I take the book for the Co SM to look at. Then to the officers mess for the officers signature I will collect it at 8:30 and proceed round the Company room ascertaining that all are present &amp; reading the orders. I will parade at 9. in front of the guest room </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P84">I/p49</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">and formally report all present to the orderly officer. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:tab/>I had to take the list of candidates for machine gun instructorship to the Orderly Room tonight my name was at the head of the list. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">Friday 21. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:tab/>Up at 5:45 and draft musketry squads on parade at 6:20. For guards parade at 8:45 the band turned out for the first time. It was a splendid morning, the thing went very well. It is great improvement it helps the inspection &amp; smartens up the step. Orderly Sergeant duties kept me occupied all the morning. After that there isn&apos;t much to do until a quarter to 5 but the compulsory to stay in is trying. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">Sat 22 </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:tab/>On Saturday 2nd Part of the L R B turned up. The battalion is back here at Patysham for a rest after a par- ticular trying time at Ypres. They were in the front trenches after the German first gas attack their particular portion being in the salient north of Zonnebeke left when the Canadians had to fall back and it was their battalion was one of those who came out of the retreat from the salient. They had very hard indeed and are now only about 350 strong out of 1400 men who came out with the falls and drafts. We hear they will now be used for lines of communication. Frost had tea with us but wasn&apos;t to me </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P87"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P88">I/p50</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">orders Sergeant I could not go out to dinner with him. We arranged however to have a dinner together when I was free. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:soft-page-break/><text:tab/>The band has come very much to the fore just lately. In fact one may say that it is the main subject of interest in the town. The columns came out in thousands when it played the men to Charnon Sunday and as a result of the welcome it got the Colonel if to play outside the barracks afterwards. On Monday also it played the guards out of the square, then came back into the square &amp; played at 8 hours till 9.15. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">Tues. 25 </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:tab/>The men who have just got their commission are here Brookshurst, Strode, Brown, Macdouglas &amp; Walsh all of them going to the 2nd West Surreys (Squires). They have just drawn &amp; are trying on their new kit, special garments to be worn for their great sacrifice. Brown is one of the men who was in my trench when we went up. White &amp; another one has already been talked with the machine gun detachment of the 1st Worcester. They go home tomorrow on leave and join their regimental alive on Sunday. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:tab/>On Thursday there was a nasty panic among the orderlies sergeants. We were all let down to start with like this. A large drill party was collected to go to Blenquey, but the SM did not make it clear that Sergeant were wanted accordingly we did not wear them. On Thurs </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P88">I/p51</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:span text:style-name="T129">and I small report all present to the orderlies officer. I had to take the list of would be machine gunmen to the SS.M. Tonight my name was at the head of the </text:span>list. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:tab/>morning however he turned out &amp; asked where our sergeants were &amp; was not rate when we told him they had not been warned or made as if fresh then out at once. Of course they were not wanted at the other end &amp; had to hang about till the host came . The next thing was that the guards parade was three men short owing to them going into the orders corporals not reporting it luckily none of them were Comen I was however set down by going roller. All corporals were wanted for guard but I had been told &amp; the corporal of the agnallers on Wed night that only one C man was available as the other had hay fever. The latter however feeling pretty fit reported himself at the orders room on Thurs for chaplain duty. The S.M immediately had all orderly sergeants brought in and complained to the adjutant about us. He listened attentively but showed that he did not consider the matter of much importance </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P88">I/p52</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:span text:style-name="T129">although he had to admit that </text:span>he told us we must be more careful and that dismissed us. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:tab/>On Sunday I was on guard at N.C Examining Post </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">June 1st </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:tab/>On Tuesday I was on drill first sent to 1915 Blondegines was then drilled for about an hour &amp; half &amp; one of the chivrons a then Mr. Asquill thanked us. We had heard the day before that he was in France and upon we got to Blondeg- gnes in the morning we heard he was visiting the school that day but we thought nothing where we were we would be out of his way. However he thanked us, escorted by Lt Gen Sir William Kel- -lington - General Staff, &amp; do the rega a lot of staff officers also by pale faced civilian. The guard was called and stood at the parade while the part walked round gazed at us A Canadian next to me was pointed out &amp; the Commandant of the School &amp; Asquill showed some interest in her. He is not at all a stature man. Short and rotelbhed he had a red face &amp; and a full nose. He struck me a looker more like a Laurel comedian than anything else. The other civilians were told was </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P88">I/p53</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">Ben Tillet but I dont know if this is true. I do however ¡of said that the latter is over here because one of our captains has been told off to pull him round. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">2 June </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:tab/>Again we went out to Glenecques as a drill party. We got back about one and were told that the officers class had been drilling for a guard of honor. Joffre and Pancasé were coming. We <text:soft-page-break/>marched down to the C.I.C. to collect them at 3 o&apos;clock. Sir William Robertson turned up with his son at three o&apos;clock, the car coming on stopping just near where I was. I got talking to the driver an old Radley boy who was studying engineering when the war began and enlisted with some influence got his present job. He told us the names of all the notabilities. Mr Squith crossed the road soon after we got there &amp; went into the C.I.C. Joffre&apos;s convoy arrived about 8:10. about 6 cars. Pancasé got out first followed by Joffre &amp; Foch. Another French general was waiting for them. They stayed well over an hour. Meanwhile the guard of honour fell out, did arms, fell out, played the national anthem. Carter was marching backwards &amp; forwards. We also saw Col. Seeler. Things began to stir again at half past four. The guard of honour fell in &amp; </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P88">I/p54</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">the people came out day 20 to five French came out to see them off with Robertson on one side and Arquill on the other there parting was most cordial Robertson&apos;s chauffeur told us that Arquill had gone all up down the line the day before and looked at reserve trenches dug in the red of our lines. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53"><text:span text:style-name="T130">3</text:span> June </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P89"><text:tab/>Having settled my nine down to a day&apos;s duty at Blendeque I was greatly relieved when I was told that Marvin wanted me to be his B.O. It was a bad day everyone was away at Blendeque so I had nothing to do after the guards Canon The S.M sent for me at a quarter to 11 - sent me down to the station to find out times of trains for the C.O. who is going home for a little few days. 11 June Green Harndford &amp; Foulshan are in bed and collecting all their kit. They leave tonight for home return to their regiment on Thursday I went down by bus to see them off at the station after a dinner at our usual place. They were all very excited but Green seemed resigned to say goodbye as we all were to them. He had a cousin send out dinner first before they left, we from Homefood </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P90">I/p55</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">25th out to cheer them and she will say that they did not deserve it? We read of the heroic deeds of the past most of them performed in the excitement of battle but I recall think that nothing can exceed the cool calculated course of these fellows. They know perfectly well that the chances of coming out one of the walking or dead are rather less than equal &amp; the chance of coming out unhurt is about ten to one against it. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>On Tues 15 Roselli suddenly left us having got a common in the ass. He goes to a place near Staples but will probably get home from there. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>Rumours of our getting leave are being revived The officers are going one by one and they send a chance if the NCOs starting too This lead to one of the greatest of the war. Peter Elmsley sent round to say that he had done all he could to get leave for the NCOs and they would materially help things but turning what the lecture room at 3:45 (the time of the colonel officers class lecture) when the </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p5<text:span text:style-name="T131">6</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">Colonel would talk to them about it. According all the sergeants who had never to common knowledge of this outside barracks searched for their belts, turned up at 3:45 only to listen to a very dull lecture from the Colonel with no mention whatever of leave. We can only think that it was a subject more of Peter to cheer the Colonel with a large audience. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>Meanwhile numerous rumours are abroad. The Colonel has just returned from a week in England; it is said that the result of his visit is that we will get no more drafts from home but all 3rd Battalion men who want commissions will be trained at Sandhurst and only 30 more will leave this battalion for the Cadet school. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>Other rumours hold out hopes of being used for active work in conjunction with the LRB &amp; Queen Westminsters. I was on guard last Monday (12/7) while these news reached us that over 110 men were being sent the following day to another </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92"><text:soft-page-break/>I/p5<text:span text:style-name="T131">7</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">advanced G.H.Q at Merville all names was original on the list but being on guard I was washed out. The men paraded just as we got back the next day and a more comic collection of soldiers you never saw. No list was allowed except what they could carry. The result was that most of them looked like a heap of dunnage. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">wed </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>All sorts of rumors are afoot concerning 16 June the disbandment of the machine gun school. We hear on excellent authority that the extra instructors will be drawn from the L.R.B &amp; Queens Westminsters, on the other hand we hear on equally good authority that we are to supply them. In any case those whose names are down paraded today for a little preliminary mustering. Personally I really do not care which way it goes. I would be very sorry to leave the battalion es- pecially if they afterwards saw some fighting, but I really do not think there is the slightest chance of this. In spite of rumors to the contrary, we hear from the 3rd battalion that they know nothing of drafts being stopped. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p5<text:span text:style-name="T131">8</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">and there seems no reason why the battalion should not continue as it has done for the last six months, to supply cadets. in spite of the fact that just at present the cadet school production of cadets at Islandeggs is much lower than it has ever been. As I say, I think the battalion will go on as it is now, supplying cadets down the G.H.Q. guards and if we get up to the machine gun school we will be doing work which is not only more interesting than the latter but also far more useful. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>As regards the question of taking a commission I really cannot reconcile myself to it. I find myself unimfluenced by the two things that have drawn so many others into it. I do not get tired of the humdrum life of a ranker and I would get but little satisfaction from displaying the plumes of an officer for some few days in England. I think these projects are too uninviting; There is no chance whatever of promotion whatever you do you begin and end your </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p5<text:span text:style-name="T131">9</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">career as an officer as a 2nd Lt. Being with a regular regiment you come in for the hardest fighting there is and in return for this what do they offer you. A hit allowance reduced to the absolute minimum and a 2 1/2 service for the time being. What you would get if totally disabled they do not state nor do they give you any other information, as far as we know the like it for granted that such considerations as these have no more weight with you than the pay with the ordinary men and man who takes a command I would be ever willing to take my chance in action as a ranker where apart from the lesser risks you are fighting side by side with your comrades and all under orders as against giving them. 22 June. From what Tyler told me today the question of the machine gun school is off. A part of ten went up on Saturday last. The same lot that went up there in consequence of a mistake some three weeks ago. These men had a three days course here some time back and according to Tyler there are a lot more still left who had the same course and will go up first if any more </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P93"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P94">career as an officer as a 2<text:span text:style-name="T4">nd</text:span> Lt Beins with a regular regiment you come in for the hardest fighting there is and in return for this what do they offer you. A kit allowance , reduced to the alsolute minimum and 2 active service a for the time being.What you would get is totla disabled they do not state nor do <text:s/>they give you any other information</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">60</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">as wanted. It seems true that about thirty men has are up there from the composite battalion i.e. L.R.B. Rangers &amp; Kensingtons 21 seems a dust but I am not the only one to be disappointed I to <text:soft-page-break/>again about it on the 25th and he was rather vague about the facts of the case but said he would make sure. I cannot help thinking that or even Wilkins may have checked to me going. The Germans have got going again with their long range guns. Dushish was shelled again on Tuesday 21 and two shots were fired at Carol these we heard, also the explosion of a shell on the afternoon of Wed which was said to be some fallen war citizens but this seems incredible. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>The list of men mentioned in dispatches was published on Wednesday it included the names of G.L. Cruchshank who was a school with me also H. Coldmay and four men who have taken commissions from the corps Messon Austin Parker &amp; Wilkins. In the honours published on Thursday. Cruchshank &amp; Messon get a military cross and W. May a C.B. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">61</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">8 july </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>Last Thursday was 25th birthday, I bought a good bath of letters and parcel from my parents from home </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>by being on guard last Monday I missed the most interesting ceremony that has taken place since we have been here. Prince Arthur the author of Connaught presented decoration to French officers. The ceremony took place in the little place and a lot chain had attended We supplied a guard of honour of 100 men under Capt. Innes who are that agreed did very well. Prince Arthur inspected them comple ment Capt. Innes and we hear from Walks that in an accident he had typed out for his sonday he described them in most flattering terms. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>Kitchener has been over here since Tuesday also Asquith and the Crown Prince of Serbia, On Fuchet in the evening unfortunately we had to arrest a drunken Sgt of the Connaught Rangers who was so drunk as to be dangerous. We took him to the Caserne d&apos;Alhet which was quite lonely but the ASC guard told us they could not take him so we had to take him onto the Banats at the city </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">62</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:span text:style-name="T129">of the Rue Carnot. As we were leaving the Algerian naval he got abusive and wished him refuge into a fire guard that I in particular as much as that the men had to take hold of him. I went of struggling and as there</text:span> seemed some chance of him getting his arms free the policeman took hold of him. He then began to ¡struggle said he wanted to ¡¡¡¡and when we refused to let him struggle so violently that he fell to the ground and cut his face after that we let him go he went quite quietly <text:tab/>The sequel was that while I was on duty 10 July first on Saturday Cpl Dove came along with a note requesting my presence before the Commandant Wm/ Sect. Co/C at 3 and he took my place while I was away. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>I had to make a statement about the ¡and Murphy was brought up to ask me questions about it. Proceeding the policeman was called then the Serg of the guard who took him over and each time Murphy was asked to question them &amp; question answer recorded Now we have to stand by </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">63</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P94">until the court marshal comes off.<text:line-break/>The whole thing blew over the colonel of the Lofe reprimanded the man &amp; he was sent back to his unit thank goodness.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P94"><text:tab/>French National day</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P94"><text:tab/>I was on gurd this morning on No4 examination post. We were just thinking about having lunch when phillip came down and told ume he had come to releave me. I had to go up to the machine gun school wisques.<text:line-break/><text:tab/>This came as a complete supprise to me as I had understood that there was no chnace of me getting up there </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92"><text:soft-page-break/>I/p6<text:span text:style-name="T131">4</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">looking out as some new found what it there are even some fellows from the officers the of us going, the put their names down long ago like I did and thinking all chance of going had disappeared they had not washed their names out. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>It appears that fourteen men from the Kenningtons and Rangers are being sent back. They came from the ¡¡G sections of the battalions but although they know a lot about the gun they would be unsuitable as in - structors </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>We had a bus to take us up to the school and were quartered in an attic though the are to move to other quarters shortly. As usual of course no one knew we were coming &amp; no provision was made for us. Fortunately a lot of the older fellows were out so we had some of their rooms. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>The school is is around old Convent a beautiful place on top of a high hill. It was built for Benedictines but was not completed before they had to leave France. It has not been occupied for 15 years. However it he </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">65</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">makes an ideal place for such a school the Chapel makes a good lecture room Roughly the plan is like this 2 incomplete Staff officers N.S. Chapel onite House quaters 2 incomplete Quad. fatigue quarters Staff quarters 2 incomplete The staff sergeants are billeted of three in vehicles and have a large mess room on the ground floor. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>This school is essentially an Artists&apos; Affair When originally started last December in St. Omar they sent to us for their first forty instructors and have drawn from us to fill vacancies ever since until three weeks ago when the Red Cross men up from </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">66</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">the LRB Rangers &amp; Kensingtons, the LRB base being kept on but the others as going back. Now tenents of us have come up to take their place. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>The school has been of here since 6th of Feb and all that time there has been a fatigue party here supplied by the artists with an Artists officer in charge, the police men and one or two gnomes for cleaning the place, so that we may remember that we run the place. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>On Thursday we went out with the instructors &amp; set up guns in selected positions around to demonstrate the notable portions for a defence to a large crowd of officers who were brought over to see it. This was the first opportunity I have had of finding out how heavy a 58th gun really is. We did exactly the same thing </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>we did the same thing but in other positions then officers &amp; men for the next course come up today. Yesterday we shifted our quarters to the 1st Sergeant, also a large room in the N end of the staff wing on the first floor Thursday 15 Friday Saturday </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">67</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">we will I think be comfortable there. The officers on the staff up here there are about 8 of them &amp; live in a separate chateau near . </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">Sundy 15 July </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>We started work in earnest today. The boys put us on to the Lewis gun, a gun which has never been taught before either here at or at Holtie and about 6 of the instructors up here have gone through a course in it so we will know something which they do not. There are all sorts of rumors as to the reason for teaching it to us but it seems probable that we will have to teach it to others very soon. There is not so much to learn in it as there is in the maxim the course will only last eight days. Monday The gun is getting familiar. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>I went into it over in the afternoon &amp; somewhere to my annoyance found that William from NWO had been made up &amp; ¡ brought into ¡ in a place where was out &amp; I got very disrupted until Walk turned up &amp; we went and had one together. Monday The gun is getting more familiar to us now We tried loading magazines and after an hour my best time was 1 min 27 sec.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P93"><text:soft-page-break/><text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T132">We started work in earnest today. They have put us on to the Lewis gun. Which was never been taught before either here or at H the, only about 6 of the instruments up here have goen through a course in it.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p6<text:span text:style-name="T131">8</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">close to his face. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">Tuesday 28 July </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>We have spent a day just playing about with the gym. We were told 52nd Ward this afternoon that we were to take the officer up here for instruction tomorrow for an hour. We will have 3 or 4 each and our instructor will just wander round in case of need. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>yesterday I heard the sad news that Cashdan who was in C Company &amp; went to the Royal Scots last month has been killed. He is the first one to go from my old hillet at 1/30 in Bullcut. He was an awfully nice fellow. Sweet as a rule but very mean on occasions, and a perfect gentleman. This makes the second casualty from a dinner party on June 11th. Cash from C/10 platoon was sent home early in the month suffering from head伤 as a result of a very severe contusion he had in the gone. although not wounded he had be knocked out by a flying sand- bag &amp; . Wednesday. Some of the original members in our faith here came to me in the evening and suggested a move in the direction of applying for leave. I had decided to approach the adjutant for myself on the grounds that </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">69</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">I would have had leave last Sunday if I had not come up here. However, I though the joint appeal a good idea so saw the adjutant early on Thursday and gave him the names of the seven of us who came out with the battalion in October. I sympathized and said he would speak to the adjutant commandant about it. In the evening he sent for me and told me to make out a list of the 42 embryo instructors including LRB Rangers stating date of arrival in France leave that had been granted This I made out &amp; gave him. On Friday he had us all in the lecture room for the benefit of the LRB Rangers who had been negotiating for leave before &amp; fully expected to get it he said that the thing would be rearranged and now would go acc- ording to the date of their arrival in France. This was a great blow to the committee and those men who had expected to go on Tuesday were muchly upset I offered to give way to a couple in the LRB if he did not go was not on the list, they have been out here since Nov 4. There has been a great panic about German aeroplanes. One flew over St. Omer on Wed night and dropped bombs all over the place all the </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">70</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">Saturdays 31/08/39 </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">people seem to have been asleep. The searchlights were never got going and no one took any steps against him. One bomb dropped quite close to our anti on the Q.M.C post and blew a house to pieces. this was only about 100 yards from the C.S.E. He also dropped a star shell in the barracks. our orderly room got the alarm &amp; sent out a part of all sorts of clothes at once to surround the site of the explosion further parties were sent out as they got dressed.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>Another aeroplane turned up at half past six on Thursday and dropped two bombs. This woke everyone up thoroughly. They applied to us for M.G.N we send down 4 teachers &amp; a Lewis Gnith team last night and have sent the same tonight. In the barracks they have started a 24 hours picket, so men from each Co have to stay up till they sleep in their boots &amp; boots with their equipment ready. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>A further aeroplane appeared today but was down off by gun fire and a British machine </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>We have had a few officers each during the last three days to instruct us the Lewis it has been very good to have. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P93">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">71</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P94"><text:soft-page-break/>We had a splendid concert last night Smiley got Kennedy Romford to come and the Maclain of Lochleive who bought with hi Lord St Jermyn The Maclain has done that sort of thing </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p7<text:span text:style-name="T131">2</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">lot of our fellows &amp; their resemblance to Tadd his son that they had some difficult in keeping straight faces. From his conversation with the commander we learnt that our government had ordered a lot of machinery but they were too late, gauges for the parts had to be made which took time and this delayed the production. We had to be content with Lewis instead. Monday. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>In order tonight the list is followed of those going on leave on Wednesday till Sunday next I am in the hot Tuesday. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>Spent the morning turning guns and went into a ones in the afternoon to do some things for Mother &amp; Marjorie. Margaret at the Ripte Candrillon went around the shops &amp; bought over four articles aproses for me to select one very good other. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">Wednesday. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>Nothing for us to do wasted in afternoon expecting to go in by 4 o&apos;clock some discovered at last minute it would not be back in time so had to set out with our hands to walk to the one station - however the was hot - however the some chel </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">73</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">eventually overtakes us when we were in Longuenese took us in. Train left at 4:53. Parlogne about 8. Had a great struggle getting out of ammunition &amp; drawing tickets got a bit to eat &amp; drink. Boat left at 10. All lights went out as we left &amp; we simply shot across 1620 min from mer to pier. Saw lights of small vessels all the way nothing else there must have been trawlers. Got alongside at Folleston soon after 11:20. Got into Victoria at 2 o&apos;c. Found free sandwiches &amp; tea very acceptable fixed to sleep in waiting room &amp; caught 5 oclock down. Thursday got home at quarter to 7 family not up so waited in garden. Magazine was already there. Had a good wash and bath. Walked over to Clatham in morning with Father and Maguire. Lines covered in troops and school filled with them. Friday 6th Went up to town by 8:23 and straight down to brewery. Hill was there alone Darnell being away. Talked to Hill and saw Mr Coupland who told me that the firm would </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">74</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">go on paying me 3/4 as by gas war lasted. Went up to town from there. Tom was away. bought a pair of boots (2/4d) and clothes at Garmages went home early. Saturday 7 Walked to Callan in morning with May, Bay, to Maidstone. Town full of troop. Had short time or never back to Maidstone to tea. Kitchener had been reviewing a parade at Malling. Found Brows &amp; Aunt Embatt home. Sunday 8 Church at 8 with Brows &amp; May. Spent morning collecting things to take back. Left with Brows at 2 40 Champ X. 413 Bought Vulture had tea strolled in LNS (12 station - seldom for little while went back at 5:15. Packed up Bunks and a lot more bagged seats in train to start at 5 to 6. Tremendous crowds seen new off, kept back 3 carlots of Temenos 1991/1 from train. Travelled down through Nunhead Cathedral Orpington to Folkepton. Boat left about 8:45 just after dark Went across ds before at around 1/2 mile. Flat calm. Train Monday 9 did not leave till 12. St. Over just before 33. walked out to school and had 2 hours sleep </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P92">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">75</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">go on paying me 3/4 as my gas was lasted. Went up to town from there. Tom was away, bought a pair of boots (2/4) and shoes at Garmages went home early. Saturday Walked to Cathan in morning with May. By to Claidstone. Town full of troops. Had short time or over &amp; back to Claidstone to tea. Kitcheners had been reviewing a parade at Malling. Found Brows &amp; Aunt Em back home. Sunday 8 </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91"><text:tab/>Church at 8 with Browns &amp; May. Spent money collecting things to take back. Left with Brows at 2 1/2 Chang X. 413 Passed Vulture had tea strolled in LSS (12 station - sat down for little <text:soft-page-break/>while went back at 5:15. Paid for Drinks and a lot more bagged seats in train to start at 5 to 6. Tremendous snowstorm. ran off, right back &amp; around of Temera 10ft from train. Travelled down through Nunhead &amp; Beechenham Orpington to Folkeston. Boat left about 8:45 just after dark Went across ds before at need have flat calm. Train already 9 did not leave till 12. St. Once just before 3. walked out to school and had 2 hours sleep </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P95">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">7</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T133">6</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P91">did not parade till 9 Put onto Mass I formal I had been given my first (tempt fenching Confirmation) on Friday 6 with Gutha, Lexington and Carson. These were first four of of the whole new bunch. I should go next in seniority to Doll. Sloan Vinh Adams Steel Stewart and Ross come after us. The time in England passed only too quickly. Mother and Father were both very well and Mayore was beautiful as ever in every way though we did not have much time together. It was such a pleasure to see the English country again he we did on the bus ride to Maidstone. Although the number of young men about was actually less both in London elsewhere. We were still undoubtedly hundreds of thousands who could be drawn upon. I did not find an enough all erroneous idea about about the war but everyone was astonished when I told them of the unfriendly attitude of the Flemish peo- -ants. Nothing at home seemed so strange after our life outside but I found that I had no appetite at all </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P95">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">7</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T133">7</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P96">Thes. 10 Went on with Max in Mill 12 &amp; then took over Self&apos;s squad of Sergeants as he was going on leave. They a good bit about it &amp; when I came to drill most of them knew more about it than I did. I fed in the Sergeants mess for the first time but it is not a place to be enthused about. In the evening we had a general meeting remarkable for the high handed way in which the President (Will) &amp; his supporters squashed all opposition. The question of admitting the embryo instructors to the mess was discussed, a fierce discussion ensued &amp; it was finally decided to leave it to the committee. Wed 11 </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P96"><text:tab/>Had interesting day with the squad. In the evening four of us Emile, Barnett, Stok &amp; myself gave a little dinner to our instructor &amp; slept down in Hafliene. It went off very well indeed although Emile had to bed early. 13. On Friday I went over to Blendeigne with Emile &amp; saw Hills, Ford and some others. Ford had an extraordinary talk to tell us an example of the discipline gone mad in force there at present. It appears that they had been out all day on some hunt without a </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P95">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">7</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T133">8</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P96">stop until about 4 o&apos;clock when the student in charge of the division was told to march them back. They stopped on the way for Ford an other man to fill their water bottles so that he could all have a drink as they went along. But happened two of the staff officers saw this &amp; it was reported. The whole school was paraded and the Commandant discussed and after saying that it was one of the two worse cases of want of discipline. Which had occurred since he had been at the school. He announced that all the offenders would be sent back to their segments. Ford and the other person of a water bottle were afterwards brought up before the Commandant &amp; he again went for them &amp; repeated the sentence However neither of these were sent back but the student in charge was. 15 Aug: </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P96"><text:tab/>On Saturday we had a mess in the Sergeant&apos;s mess which developed in a drinking spree. Sunday. Went into the town to see the fellow officers were leaving the school. After Townsend left Lager was among them. I saw Wallis afterwards, it appears quite true that he was married &amp; he he was at home. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P95">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T131">7</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T133">9</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P96">Monday. Concert given by the officers in the hall which again developed into a drinking orgy. The entertainment as on Saturday was of a very moderate order. We have had two or three entertainments given in the grounds here of the Grenadier Guards&apos; Barracks. They came out with a <text:soft-page-break/>defence scheme. They have small sand bags with a short, blunt fuse which makes when hit. Their throwing is simply non- defensive but it is quite obvious that the slaughter in these engagements is really terrific. On Friday they had the stunt at night: The lit flares which pro- duced a wonderful effect in the trees and rochets. The fight ended with four defenders left alive &amp; all the attack killed. One of the defenders left was a Corporal who after overcoming all the apparents mounted guard on the end of the trench with a revolver taken from an officer he had knocked out. Saturday. 21 Aug. On Saturday we had the concert of the course. It was not so good as last course we missed Ronfard but it was very good all the same &amp; went very well. I was looking after Ladish </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P97">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T133">80</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P96">who had come up from the trenches with to correct part. There is a regiment of French territorial soldiers round here digging trenches. They are carrying out a scheme of defence for Calais and Boulogne. They are certainly making some exceptionally strong trenches protected by pits and stakes. On Sunday we spent the morning on the range in the afternoon I played. In the evening we heard heavy gun fire from the firing line. Tuesday On Tuesday I went into St Omer to see the dentist 24 May I made an arrangement for Friday. I got back to Wagres to lunch (2 hours to walk) and after lunch I walked with Lance to The Bourne. It was a very good walk but the place is very uninteresting now. It is at present the head quarters of the Sarah Gals who need their form each night. Coming back we tried to cut straight across from Petit Bois to Malines but found two tremendous hollows on the way. They looked like old merlons one was about 200 and 200 ft deep. When I got back I found I had been wanted to go down to St Omer with guns as an anti-aircraft guard. Lewington had </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P95">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T133">81</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P96">who had come up from the trenches with to correct part. There is a regiment of French territorial soldiers round here digging trenches. They are carrying out a scheme of defence for Calais and Boulogne. They are certainly making some exceptionally strong trenches protected by pits and stakes. On Sunday we spent the morning on the range in the afternoon I played. In the evening we heard heavy gun fire from the firing line. Tuesday On Tuesday I went into St Omer to see the dentist 24 May I made an arrangement for Friday. I got back to Wagres to lunch (2 hours to walk) and after lunch I walked with Lance to The Bourne. It was a very good walk but the place is very uninteresting now. It is at present the head quarters of the Sarah Gals who need their form each night. Coming back we tried to cut straight across from Petit Bois to Malines but found two tremendous hollows on the way. They looked like old merlons one was about 200 and 200 ft deep. When I got back I found I had been wanted to go down to St Omer with guns as an anti-aircraft guard. Lewington had </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P95">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T133">82</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P96">off two o&apos;clock I took over the duty of instructing some of the new instructors who where teaching guardmen. In the evening the Scots guard had a dinner in the officers men and had their superiors there they played in the dining hall I only noticed the signatures I noticed C.W. Blackworth Reed Sunday Went into St Omar in afternoon and saw some more fellows off at the station. M A Hillel, Case Podd &amp; Ford were among them, it made me more sure with the commission business than ever. I saw Wallis afterwards and walked back with Dangefield. I had started with a new class in the morning they were all Scotsmen from the 4th division the first New Army division out here. They have come up for a four day course in the Lewis as they expect to be served out with this gun shortly. They are a fine lot of fellows two of them being remarkably fine men. They are smart too The time table was badly arranged &amp; Capt Maggiciridy among other things he only gave us one hour on staff pages </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P95">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T133">83</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P96">Thursday I have a day off today. It is a dull day. Several of the engineers have gone to Bethune on the horses which have taken the shot deans corpse back they will return on the horses tonight with the new lot. I am down for duty on the roof of St. Omer tonight but it is sure to be washed out it is such a bad day. Friday Started on a new squad today officers this time belonging to London territorial battalions excepting the 47 D. O. It is a bad day and we have to wash inside one officer went sick he has a form of typhoid Saturday Another very bad day in the evening the commandant gave a concert to the officers of the guards division; it was a great success which went very well and there was an excellent violinist a Frenchman from the Paris Opera House I have never heard a better player. The Welsh guards and singers were there too and gave several choruses. They are <text:soft-page-break/>wonderful, keep perfect time and have a splendid tone. The Prince of Wales was present - I was very taken with him. He pushed in with the crowd </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P98">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T133">84</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P96">and I did not notice him. Coming out he pushed through with the other officers when he saw we were watching for him. He shot out of the door sideways in a most undignified but charmingly boyish manner. On Sunday one of my officers asked me to go into St. James with him together with one of the other - have you. I have been giving him extra time and this was my of acknowledged. We went to the Grand St. Louis where we used to go. We have been having the guns a lot lately they have been having a tempest according to the papers. Friday and Saturday were frightfully wet it rained all day both days and the general has got ooched it will not help things at all. Tuesday I have had a joy ride today. Our short squad was going back on buses and we got permission to go back with them. It was a beautiful day and we had a very enjoyable ride. We went through some a Lullers to Bethune we stopped there for half an hour. It is a bright town much more French </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P98">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T133">8</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T58">5</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P96">than Bailloul, it has been shelled a little but, not much. We went on from there to Houckin where we put our people down this was only about 3 miles behind the line. They are in a house there on the side of the hill a very nice spot when the weather is good H.C. Partridge is there and I said him before we moved off. The village was not a very bright spot but it showed no signs of shelling at all. When we had put our parts down we started back even after two and return to Bethune through Drouvin. We stopped for about half an hour when we got through Bethune and left again about 3 30. Between Bethune &amp; Lillers to the south of the road are two wonderful things which can be seen for miles we can see them in fact at Wignies. The buses dropped us at Longuenesse and we walked back to the front across the flying ground getting in about 7. 21- was really a splendid ride the country was much better than I expected and although we did not see very much of the war what we did see was interesting. We got quite familiar with the winter campaigning as when we were at Bailloul but the summer life we had not seen. Everywhere were </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P98">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T133">8</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T58">6</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">livornacs and the men seemed quite comfortable of course it must have been horrible during the 48 hours rain last week. Wed. New squads arrive the belong to the 24 division and have not been up to the trenches yet in feel they have only been out here about a fortnight. They have had the Lewis guns for about 3 months so they can&apos;t learn much, they they so at any rate. There is quite a difference between them and the men we get back here from the trenches the latter are of course very pleased to be here but beyond that they are not nearly as perky. Sunday 12 Sept We have heard a lot of heavy firing lately particularly on Frogs Saturday mornings. Our boys know all squads left us yesterday, they were suddenly recalled &amp; in were not sorry. A curious thing item appeared in orders tonight C G H Kent. Arthur was recommended by Gen C. Euston for an act of heroism in rescuing a French soldier from the lock on C 105 Examining Post. This is the fellow known as Bacchus a lover in private life Monday. We are supposed to be going to make a tremendous 135th attack tomorrow I wonder what will become of it</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P98">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T133">8</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T58">7</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">I have never said anything about my bed, I have had it about 13 weeks now. I had to buy two rails from the village carpenter two metres long about 4&quot; broad and 1/2&quot; thick the rest of the material is made up of ration boxes. The legs a pieces of the sides of jam boxes the being about the stoutest stuff the ration boxes yield. The top of the bed is boarded in with sides of Maronite boxes Biscuit box sides are about 1/2 longer some to strengthen pieces for the legs &amp; frame. This makes it about 21 broad not quite as broad as my mothers but- quite broad enough, and it stands about 18&quot; off the floor. I boarded it so that it would be more useful as a seat than if it were of canvas and this has <text:soft-page-break/>proved most convenient as it happens because we have had to give up all the benches tables in the room. Then again by having a rigid top I can put all sorts of things underneath While I was making it the other fellow tried to nag me about it &amp; said it would collapse</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P98">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T133">8</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T58">8</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">but there are three or four mutations of it now. Beside my bed is an old music box on end with a board top nailed to it which makes a useful table I have put shelves in the box and use by and two as drawers. These help to keep my things truly handy. Wednesday Started on a squad of officers of the Coldstream Guards they were very stand offish at first and I never really settled down with them during the four days I had them. They seemed to find the fatigue part of the summer particularly tiresome &amp; were always upset when they got their rounds dirty. Two of them were old cadets one a man named Hallyn the other G P Fildes who is the heir a son of Duke Fildes the R.A. Sunday 19 Today I have started on a new squad of NCOs from the 17-19 Dws. The latter came from normal Fortunest the day an attack had been arranged for last week but it was washed out at the last moment. Today we had a group taken of the whole staff A lot of people left the school at Blenhe- mies today among them Jimmy Hunter. They are very disappointed because they are being sent </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P98">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T133">8</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T58">9</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">to pitchers, this is a disgraceful business. They might have enlisted in this month ago and become captains &amp; now instead of that they are temp Lieutenants with no hope of promotion &amp; must remain junior to all the privates who are in their battalions already. It rather amuses me when her little gulkes smile are taking the Colt this course have been much annoyed because they are always finding that the gun has been interfered with by people who knows nothing about it and parts are lost . Today they came out of a lecture to find once again that it had been interferes with they thought it time something was done so told Cooper the supervising S. I. he went to Capt. Me ¡ and told him what had happened said it was always occurring and would he give an order that it was never to be touched the commandant was there at the time and Megill made futile efforts to check him and when he had finished told him. Oh I was working on the Colt myself this afternoon. Wed. I had to go down to St. Omar in the evening </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P98">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T58">90</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P96">on the anti aircraft again I went to the college st Boston The sentries were supplied of the battalion DC Hill being in charge We heard a fierce bombardment- going on before two o&apos;clock Saturday 25 There has been a lot of artillery action for the past fortnight but last night they started about 6 o&apos;clock in the evening &amp; hell as a continuous roar until 8 o&apos;clock this morning it seemed to die down for a lil- but started again about 12 &amp; has gone on ever since It was announced at the end of the lecture at 12 this morning that we had ¡after been using gas this morning followed by a bombardment - had taken three lines of trenches over a 20. mile front the announcement was received with cheers and everyone has been in very high spirit Sunday yesterday evening we heard that - a German counter attack at La Barnee had been successful. The guns have been quiet comparatively quiet today with occasional vigorous bursts. We have had no further news- Over 200 Artiste have been sent to arrive to unload munitions. The remainder are only allowed out </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P98">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T58">91</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P96">for 2 hours at a time. The Kennington LRB have more off it is reported to exert pressure. Monday It was announced at lecture today that the Germans had thrown all their available reserves against us and that the French were continuing to make good progress in Champagne. We We had captured a large amount of material and large numbers of men and several guns. We are eagerly waiting for the papers tomorrow. Tuesday The papers have broken out with tremendous headlines TWO REAL VICTORIES AT LAST says the Daily Mail. The number of guns taken altogether is said to be 9 &amp; 2600 men the French have taken 1200 men. The French official report published late last night gives the guns captured as 78 including 23 by the British while the late report on Sunday gave the <text:soft-page-break/>prisoners as over 20,000 unwounded including 200 officers. Yesterday&apos;s report says the officers number 200. The Germans have made vigorous counter attacks in Champagne &amp; have even broken the French line in some places but on the whole the French are making steady progress. Meanwhile the Germans are holding us at Loos &amp; Halheul. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P98">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T58">92</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P96">went I walked into St. Omer in the evening. The town was more miserable than ever. All the lights have to be shaded and several shops I wanted to go to were shut. I went down to the barracks &amp; saw Hulls he had no news of MA. I then looked up. Capt. Oostle has been wounded. I was told that several of the latter officers who had gone up with the gas corps had had an exciting time. He wounded they said have been pouring into St. Omer. The fatigue that had been to Arques had just returned. They had been changing the fuses on 18 lb shells. A lot of these fuses had given trouble bursting in the gun. They now were working on 8 hour shifts &amp; had a pretty tough time. I went out with Hulls &amp; bought a paper before I went back. There was no fresh news except that the Russians have been doing well. There was one report from Sgt. J. French giving our captures as 53 officers 2500 men 18 guns &amp; 32 M.Gs. It was a very wet night &amp; I got very wet getting back in spite of my machintosh Wed. The rain continued all night and all </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P98">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T58">93</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P96">today almost without a day. We have heard no cannonading since Sunday and the rain must I should think interfere to a great extent with our plans. All sorts of rumours are afoot but we take no notice of anything except the official reports. Copies of the French reports are handed up in the hall. I have had a splendid squad this course. They are NCOs belonging to the 2nd New Army 14/19 Division one man, so ¡ ¡ a Welsh miner is the best of the bunch he is a cockney but a wonderfully smart fellow a very clever with his hands the others are all good too. We did the Zens for 6 days I have been on the Maxim since this is the first chance I have had of getting any consecutive instruction in this &amp; I do not find it difficult. On Friday Self Smythe Burrows returned the base from with the 25th Division for a week down near Amiens we have taken over part of the line there from a point some way south of Stres right down to Albert. On Saturday we had our usual end of course concert it was not as good as usual. ¡ parts of it have been away for two days. They went down to Sauly. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P61">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T102">94</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">beyond Bethune &amp; quite close to the scene of the recent fighting. They some had to teach others had to clean up guns which had been in a temble and had been handed over to some people who knew nothing about the gun. They did not have an exciting time themselves although two shells went over their billet. Sundays 3-0-1. This afternoon I walked down to Stomer with the idea of seeing Kettle off one of the men from the battalion last night. told me he had got a commission in the ASC but I was leaving this afternoon He told me when I saw him on Tuesday that he had put in for it &quot;also matter of fact I not see him. I met A P Hunter on the platform He was going down to offenible to stand duties as R.T.O. He told me he had seen Kettle off in the morning so I had no hope for getting I had some tea &amp; came straight back. A lot cause started here today the case from the 15th Div. were in the recent fighting. It seems from what they say that some temble mistakes were made some regiments lost The case also bad later about the behaviour of the some of the battalions of the 21st Div. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P61">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T102">95</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">The Weekly papers in their leading articles talk as if the advance last week was only a preliminary operation in a much greater scheme, we will wait and see. The weather during the past week has been wet. It has rained nearly every day the country has got very muddy it must be very bad up at the front. Mon. 4 The casualty list today includes the names of four of the old platoon who went to the Queen Brown &amp; Walsh killed - Broachlehurst wounded. Two of the officers I had from the 3rd to the 6th of last month have also been killed. I was very sorry to hear about Brown. He was a very good sort. He was in my trench when we were in the trenches he is the second to be killed. The other Whittle went some time ago. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P61">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T102">96</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">Commission No 11 Platoon Men who arrived with No 2 &amp; subsequent drafts Simpson Trinder Burnett 2nd Border. Killed June 15 ( in England ) 7th North F. 12 H Maddock. 4 J.B.M. Walsh 2nd West Surrey Killed 26 Sep 17 H. Battcombe. E.C. Foulsham Suffolk 13/6/15 W.C Green 1st East Yorks &quot; L.G. Hannaford. &quot; Wounded 15 Feb 15 at home L.D Watt. 2nd E Surrey Regt. 9. Threlfallon Pratt XIV Duke of Cornwall Molnix Pratt Benson 4. VI. 15 D C B Ferguson. 1st Buffs. Wounded July H.F.P Ford 1st Buffs. 29/8/15 Hospital EK Smith 1st Buffs. S.H. Dawson. 1st 12 Warhuh Hospital 25.VIII. N.E. Rosselli A.S.C. 13.VI.15 Cafford 1st East Kent (Cuffs) 15/8/15 </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P61">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T102">97</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P53">South Lane 2nd Sketch 29/8/11 2nd West Yorks.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P61">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T102">98</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P61">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T102">99</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P99">F Coy and F/801 draft. 92 men Commissions E Coy. 13 Nov-14 CorpL CorpL Grenadier Guards Killed 9/1/15: Pte Rees Killed 24/1/15: L Gohl S Horsley 2nd Gordons Wounded 16/3/15: Pte O Horsley 2nd Gordons Williams 2nd Bedford Wounded 18/1/15: 2nd Bedford Involved 20/7/15 Bird (To England) 1 Jan 15 J.A. Hutchinson 2nd Black Watch EL Kelke 1st Bedfords Killed 19/1/15 H.V. Hutt Royal Sussex Killed 3/1/15 LE Taylor Royal Sussex Wounded 18/1/15 K.S. Broad Leinster 2nd Wounded 24/1/15 CS Birch 1st Bedfords Killed 29/1/15 J.T. Cole Devons Injured 2nd Janis FG Mann N Staffs Killed 12/3/15 A.H. Eames 2nd Gordons Wounded 14/6/15 W Roseoe 2nd South Lancs Wounded 24/1/15 AC Soulby 1st Ldn Rifles Wounded 4/1 15 Feb N N Wimbish 2nd KO Royal Lancs Wounded - 14/6/15 WB Trulshawe 1st Liverpools Wounded W.T. Colyer 2nd R Dublin Fus. Wounded 13/5/15 R.M. Goodman 2nd Border Killed 14/5/15 B.C. Wood 2nd D.C.L.T. </text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P61">I/p<text:span text:style-name="T102">100</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P99"/>
  </office:text>
 </office:body>
